      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sharing the Wealth</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof George Levinger letter disputes Charles W Kadlec's August 1 Op-Ed article supporting repeal of estate tax and lowering of income taxes because he thinks poor, not just rich, will benefit (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Charles W. Kadlec (''How Taxes Trickle Down,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 1) supports the repeal of the estate tax and the lowering of income taxes because he thinks the poor, not just the rich, will benefit.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Charles W. Kadlec (''How Taxes Trickle Down,'' Op-Ed, Aug. 1) supports the repeal of the estate tax and the lowering of income taxes because he thinks the poor, not just the rich, will benefit.</p>
        <p>However, the wealthiest 1 percent of Americans doubled their share of our country's wealth between 1976 and 1997 (from 19 percent to 40 percent), while the share of the bottom 90 percent plunged from 51 percent to 27 percent.</p>
        <p>Furthermore, the estate tax is paid by only a tiny minority of people, those lucky enough to be born in wealthy families. Why shouldn't they share their good fortune with the rest of society?</p>
        <p>GEORGE LEVINGER  Amherst, Mass., Aug. 1, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is professor emeritus of social psychology at the University of Massachusetts.</p>
      </block>
